ndia is to emerge as a model for other parts of the world, a "binding morality" that reaches beyond the current environmental crisis will be required. Empathy for marginalized underclasses-Dalits, poor Muslims, landless migrants-who live, almost invisibly, amid waste produced predominantly for the comfort of the better-off will be the critical element in India's relationship with waste. Solutions will arise at the intersection of the traditional and the cutting edge, policy and practice, science and spirituality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aCastezIndia. 0aElectronic books. 0aRefuse and refuse disposalzIndia. 0aRefuse and refuse disposal-India. 0aSalvage (Waste, etc.)zIndia. 0aSalvage (Waste, etc.)-India. 0aSewage disposalzIndia. 0aSewage disposal-India. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060662140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674986022?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674986022423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674986022/original  a978-3-11-060662-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles